ms In the Realm of the Senses and The Empire of Passion, Oshima engages issues of sexuality and power, domination and identity, which Maureen Turim explores in relation to psychoanalytic and postmodern theory. The films' complex representation of women in Japanese society receives detailed and careful scrutiny, as does their political engagement with the Japanese student movement, postwar anti-American sentiments, and critiques of Stalinist tendencies of the Left. Turim also considers Oshima's surprising comedies, his experimentation with Brechtian and avant-garde theatricality as well as reflexive textuality, and his essayist documentaries in this look at an artist's gifted and vital attempt to put his will on film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a20th century japanese art history.  a20th century japanese film.  aanti american sentiments.  abrechtian theatricality.  acultural iconoclasm.  acultural studies.  acultural tensions.  afilmic style.  aidentity.  ain the realm of the senses.  ajapanese student movement.  aoshima nagisa.  apolitical engagement.  apolitics.  apostmodernism.  apostmodernity.  apostwar japanese art.  apostwar japanese cinema.  apsychoanalysis.  areflexive textuality.  arepresentations of women.  asexuality and power.  asocially daring.  athe empire of passion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020666340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918283?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918283/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_Y